    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-12-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="466"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d466">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Leishman</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-12-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 2, 1905</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1218.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of the
                    department’s telegram of November 27, 1905, as per copy on overleaf, also
                    dispatch of November 15, upon the question of schools and privileges for
                    beneficent institutions, and referring especially to the proposed Jesup hospital
                    at Beirut.</p>
                <p>While the question of equality of treatment for American charitable institutions
                    was satisfactorily settled, in principle, by the Porte’s note of August 15,
                        1904,<note n="a" xml:id="d466fna">Printed in <ref target="frus1904#pg_830"
                            >Foreign Relations, 1904, p. 830</ref>.</note> the matter of putting the
                    decree into practical execution has been dragging along, despite the constant
                    and earnest efforts of this legation to force the Porte to accomplish the
                    necessary formalities of transferring the titles of the different properties
                    into the names of the several institutions, etc.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John G. A. Leishman</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
